Dear Sir:
take no offence if I take
the opportunity of writing a few lines
to you wherein I wish to state a few
remark concerning the case of Trooper
FitzPatrick against Mrs. Kelly W.
Skillion & W.lliamson and to state
the facts of the case to you. It seems
impossible for me to get any justice
without I make a statement to
some one that will take notice
of it as it is no use in me
complaining about anything that
the Police may choose to say or swea
against me and the public in their
ignorance and blindness will
undonbtedly back them up to
their utmost. No doubt I am
now placed in very peculiar
circumstances and you might
blame me for it but if you knew
how I have been wronged andL persecuted
you would say I cannot be blamed
In April last an information was
(which must have come under your
notice) lworn against me for
shooting trooper Fitzpatrick which
was false and my mother with an
infant baby and brother in-law
& another neighbour was taken for
aiding and abetting and attempting
to minder him a charge of
they are as purely innocent as
the child unborn. During my stay
on the King River I run in a wild
null which I gave to Lydicher who
afterwards sold him to Carr & he killed
him for beef. Cometine afterwards I
was told I was blamed for Stealme
this ball from Whitty I asked Whitty on
Moyhu racecourse why he blamed me
for stealing his Reill he said he had
found his ball and he never blames
me for stealing him. He said it
was Daniell who told him that I
stole the Uull. Cometinie afterwards
I heard again I was blamed for
stealing a mob of calves from Whitty
and Farrell which I never had anything
to do with and along with this and
other talk I began to think they
wanted something to talk about.
Whitty and Burns not being satisfied
with all the picked land on King
River and Boggy breek and the run
of their stock on the certificate yours
efree and no one interfering with them
Paid heavy rent for all the open ground
so as a poor man could not keep any
stock and impounded every beast
they could catch even off
sovenment
road if a poor man happened to
itesse his horse or bit of a poddy calf
untoide his paddock it would be
impounded. I have known over 60 head
of horses to be in one day impounded
by Whitly and Burn's all belonging to
to poor men of the district they would
have to leave their harvest or
ploughing and go to Oeler and then
perhaps not have money enough to
Release them & have to give a bill of
Sale or boorow the money which is no
easy matter & alone with all this sort

horse from George King and had him

at How long and the rest was sold

anyman requiring horses would have

I was tried at Beeckworth on the 9th October 1878 on
a charge of aiding and abetting the Kellys and with an Attempt to Murder and
sentence to six years hard labor. The day on which the offence was alleged to
have been committed I was eplitting wood on the lange about a quarter of a
miele from Kellys house when constable Fitzpatrick rode up and asked if I
had a splitters licence. I told him that I was not aware one was required.
He replied that he did not care but I had better not let the Creta fellows know,
15th meaning the Greata police. He called with me for about ten minutes and then
I started in the direction of Greta. I started for home shortly afterwards. It was
now about sundown. When I got near Mrs Kelly's house I saw Skillion coming
across the paddock and I spoke to him and while thus engaged Fitzpatrick
rode up to the fence and asked if Skillion had seen any strange horses and
he replied "No". Fitzngatuck then asked where Dan Kelly was. I saw
Mrs Kelly at the door and asked her if Dan was in. She did not answer;
but Dan came out and Fitzpatrick called him over to him. Skillion started
away at this time towards home. I heard Fitzpatruck say something about
a warrant and Dan said he would have something to eat before he went.
Fitzpatrick said he would give him a goodapper in Greba. Dan said it
was looked and he might as well have it. They were then both going towards
the house. When they reached there Mrs. Kelly tried to keep Fitzpatrick out
when he drew his Gevolver and threatened to shoot her. She then took a
spade and was going to hit him with it when I stopped in between them
and took it from her and threw it behind the fire. Two of Mrs. Kellys children,
two and four years of age were scheaning. I took them in my arms and went
out of the house to quiet them. Soon after this Ned Kellyrushed round
at Fitzpatrick
the corner of the house to the door and fired two shots I left the children
and was going towards the house when a man named King passed me with a

Of Fitzpatucks revolver. Dan had hold of his right arm and Mrs. N.Y.
